"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is fundamental to 3D vision, yet accurately estimating depth in non-Lambertian and mixed scenes remains challenging due to complex reflectance properties. Existing methods predominantly rely on strict Lambertian assumptions and partial-view epipolar plane image architectures, causing severe performance degradation and feature ambiguity in specular or scattering regions. To address this, a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model integrated with a Multi-scale Angular Cost Volume Network (MACVO-Net) was proposed, which introduced dual-mask physical modeling coupled with an MRI-inspired angular frequency analysis to classify materials via 2D-DFT spectral energy. Furthermore, a staged training strategy was employed with a guided training mechanism for adaptive energy adjustment, while MACVO-Net leveraged all 81 angular views to construct an explicit cost volume, utilizing flat cost signals in non-Lambertian regions as uncertainty priors. Extensive experiments across five datasets demonstrate that our method achieves a state-of-the-art mean absolute error of 0.281567 with merely 600K parameters, while the material classification accuracy reaches 88.235294%. This work fundamentally breaks the Lambertian restriction by unifying physical optical modeling with full-angular coherence, significantly enhancing depth estimation robustness and physical interpretability in complex scenes.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflectance, Dual-mask physical modeling, Angular cost volume, Guided training"